President Joe Biden has appointed individuals to key regional leadership roles at the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA). These appointees will play a crucial role in the administration's efforts to rebuild communities impacted by the pandemic, support economic recovery, and address climate change. The regional appointees bring extensive expertise in their respective areas and have strong relationships with federal, state, tribal, and local leaders. They also reflect the diversity of America and the communities they serve. The USDA's Farm Service Agency implements agricultural policy and manages various programs across each U.S. state. State Executive Directors oversee this work to ensure the equitable distribution of USDA resources. The Rural Development mission area of the USDA focuses on improving the economy and quality of life in rural America. State Directors lead offices that provide grants, loans, and loan guarantees to support economic development and essential services. The appointed individuals include Ronald Guidry, Jr. as USDA State Executive Director for Louisiana, Maureen Wicks for Montana, Mark Gibbons for Utah, Christy Davis for Kansas, and Lillian Salerno for Texas. Each appointee has a background in agriculture and a track record of working to strengthen their respective communities.